711716f-a.text:
West 23rd Street, north side, west from but not including Ninth, to, but not including Tenth Aves.  This row of buildings were known as Chelsea Terrace.

About 1923.

Eugene L Armbruster, Collection.

711707f-a.text:
23rd Street, north side, west from Ninth Avenue. At right is the original London Terrace, a row of cottages and apartment houses built in 1845 by Bishop Clement C. Moore, author of "The Night before Christmas". These houses were modeled on similar structures popular in London at the time, and for many years constituted a very fashionable address. They were demolished in 1929 and 1930, and replaced by a series of large, modern apartment houses which retain the name London Terrace.

About 1927.

Price Studios, Inc.
Neg.  #1134

711710f-a.text:
361 West 23rd Street, east of the N.E. corner of Ninth Ave, Building concerned was formerly the Pasteur Institute and at one time the residence of Mrs. Lantry.

About 1923.

Eugene L. Arbruster, Collection

711712f-a.text:
361-363 West 23rd Street, north side, east of Ninth Avenue. This house was the residence of the theatrical producer James Fisk; after his assassination, it was owned by the famous actress Lily Langtry. It is now the Rosse Cruces Club, and will by 1935 be demolished.

About 1925.
